ARCommand - Class in com.parrot.arsdk.arcommands
Java representation of a C ARCommand object.
This class holds either app-generated objects, that are to be sent to the device, or network-generated objects, that are to be decoded by the application.
ARCommand() - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arcommands.ARCommand
Creates a new, empty ARCommand with the default size.
This is a typical constructor for app-generated ARCommand.
To optimize memory, the application can reuse an ARCommand object after it was disposed.
ARCommand(int) - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arcommands.ARCommand
Creates a new, empty ARCommand with an user-specified size.
This is a typical constructor for app-generated ARCommand.
To optimize memory, the application can reuse an ARCommand object after it was disposed.
ARCommand(ARNativeData) - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arcommands.ARCommand
Creates a new ARCommand from another ARNativeData instance.
This is a typical constructor for network-generated ARCommand.
To optimize memory, the application can reuse an ARCommand object after it was disposed.
ARCommand(long, int) - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arcommands.ARCommand
Creates a new ARCommand from a c pointer and size.
To optimize memory, the application can reuse an ARCommand object after it was disposed.
ARCommand(ARNativeData, int) - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arcommands.ARCommand
Creates a new ARCommand from another ARNativeData, with a given minimum capacity.
This is a typical constructor for network-generated ARCommand.
To optimize memory, the application can reuse an ARCommand object after it was disposed.

ARNativeData - Class in com.parrot.arsdk.arsal
Root class for all C data that may pass through different libs of AR.SDK

AR.SDK Is mainly implemented in C, and thus libs often use C structures to hold data.
This is a wrapper class onto these kind of data, so java can pass them around libs without copy into JVM memory space.
ARNativeData(int) - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arsal.ARNativeData
Generic constructor
This constructor allocate a ARNativeData with the given capacity
ARNativeData() - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arsal.ARNativeData
Default size constructor This constructor allocate a ARNativeData with the default capacity
ARNativeData(ARNativeData) - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arsal.ARNativeData
Copy constructor
This constructor creates a new ARNativeData with a capacity
equal to the original objects data size
ARNativeData(long, int) - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arsal.ARNativeData
Copy constructor (from native)
This constructor creates a new ARNativeData with a capacity
equal to the original data size
ARNativeData(ARNativeData, int) - Constructor for class com.parrot.arsdk.arsal.ARNativeData
Copy constructor, with specified allocation size
This constructor creates a new ARNativeData with a capacity
equal to the greatest value between the specified capacity and the original
object data size

ARStreamReader - Class in com.parrot.arsdk.arstream
Wrapper class for the ARSTREAM_Reader C object.

To create an ARStreamReader, the application must provide a suitable ARStreamReaderListener to handle the events.

The two ARStreamReader Runnables must be run in independant threads

didUpdateFrameStatus(ARSTREAM_READER_CAUSE_ENUM, ARNativeData, boolean, int, int) - Method in interface com.parrot.arsdk.arstream.ARStreamReaderListener
This callback can be called in different cases:
- Frame complete:
- 'currentFrame' contains a complete frame and won't be used by ARStreamReader again
- 'isFlushFrame' is true if the complete frame occured after a buffer flush (on most cases, the complete frame is an I-Frame)
- 'nbSkippedFrames' contains the number of skipped frames since the last complete frame
- 'newBufferCapacity' is undefined
- Return value is the storing location of the next frame
- Frame too small:
- 'currentFrame' should not be modified (it is still used by the ARStreamReader)
- 'isFlushFrame' is undefined
- 'nbSkippedFrames' is undefined
- 'newBufferCapacity' holds a suitable capacity for the new buffer.
- Return value is a new ARNativeData, greater than the currentFrame buffer.
-- If the returned value is null or smaller than currentFrame, the frame is discarded
- Copy complete: (only called after a Frame too small)
- 'currentFrame' is the previous frame buffer, which can now be freed (or reused)
- 'isFlushFrame' is undefined
- 'nbSkippedFrames' is undefined
- 'newBufferCapacity' is undefined
- Return value is unused and should be null
- Cancel:
- 'currentFrame' is the frame buffer which is cancelled, and which can be freed
- 'isFlushFrame' is undefined
- 'nbSkippedFrames' in undefined
- 'newBufferCapacity' is undefined
- Return value is unused and should be null
didUpdateFrameStatus(ARSTREAM_SENDER_STATUS_ENUM, ARNativeData) - Method in interface com.parrot.arsdk.arstream.ARStreamSenderListener
This callback can be called in two different cases:
- Frame sent:
The frame was successfully sent to the reader
- Frame cancel:
The frame was cancelled before it was acknowledged
This does not ensure that the frame was not received.

setTimeBetweenRetries(int, int) - Method in class com.parrot.arsdk.arstream.ARStreamSender
Sets the minimum and maximum time between retries.
Setting a small retry time might increase reliability, at the cost of network and cpu loads.
Setting a high retry time might decrease reliability, but also reduce the network and cpu loads.
These rules apply to both the minimum and the maximum time.
